{
    "_id" : ObjectId("60364ccb0c817f0398fa54ff"),
    "job_link" : "https://www.quora.com/What-are-career-opportunities-for-the-role-of-technical-business-analyst?-",
    "answer" : "The role of a Business Analyst is a messy one and rarely clearly defined in any organization. Some will want technical skills, sometimes to extreme - what they really want is a developer who has analytical skills (a rarity), or you will see many job postings that include a lot of requirements that fit in to the role of a Quality Assurance person. The BA role has always been a confusing and poorly defined space. If you are technical and you enjoy doing analyst work (which is exactly how I roll), then I suggest actually  searching for positions that are titled \"Technical Business Analyst\" or \"Business Systems Analyst\" as these are types of roles are usually going to allow you to utilize your analysis and technical skills.   If you aren't technical, then quickly scan those postings and move on. Do not take jobs that require skills you don't enjoy using. Which is not the same as saying don't take a job where you don't have the required skills. Job postings are \"wish lists\" and are almost always flexible. The same goes for so-called education requirements. I have no degree, but I do have 140+ hours of college credit - I don't have a degree but I do have an extensive education.  The only time I skip over a position with a degree requirement is when they are looking for someone with a Masters or higher, because clearly they want a degree higher than my level of education and putting a Masters+ as a requirement also usually means that they aren't going to negotiate the education level. One more thing to consider is the difference between having a Technical Skill (I can write SQL queries, complex SQL queries, build databases) versus having an understanding of a technical skill (I can read SQL queries, work with result sets to create reports, analyze the data that comes from the database). Many job postings will ask for a Technical BA, and what they really want is someone who has a deep understanding of technology, not necessarily being able to perform the work of a technologist. So be sure and read specific requirements carefully to determine which they really want: Prior experience working in a SQL environment and creating reports from data sets using a variety of tools.Prior experience writing creating SQL queries, extracting data, using Tableau to create reports and design dashboards.The first wants understanding and some skill and using the data results to analyze and create reports. The second is asking for a hard technical skill, you will be writing queries, extracting data, etc...  In my case, for example, I can write SQL and complex SQL, but I can only read code, I used to write code a long time ago, but I have no practical skill today that allows me to create actual code.  So back to the question - what are career opportunities for a tech BA - here are some common  job titles you might see: Technical Business AnalystSenior Technical Business AnalystBusiness Systems AnalystSenior Business Systems AnalystBusiness Process Analyst for Technology TeamBusiness Process Analyst for IT DepartmentThose are just a  few of the potential job titles you will find. Here are a couple of great websites that you can explore for more information on the role of a Business Analyst.  The Professional Association dedicated to promoting the business analysis profession worldwide - IIBA  Bridging the Gap  Business Analyst Certification | PBA   Good luck!",
    "date" : ISODate("2021-02-24T12:55:39.818Z"),
    "question" : "What are career opportunities for the role of technical business analyst? ",
    "source" : "Quora"
}

